 xmlns:trans="http://docbook.org/ns/transclusion">
  <info>
    <title>Inserting the memory module</title><!-- can be changed via merge
in the assembly -->
    <!-- add author's e-mail -->
    <meta name="maintainer" content="jsindelarova@suse.com" its:translate="no"/>
    <abstract><!-- can be changed via merge in the assembly -->
      <para>
       Once the system is configured and running, you can perform the physical installation. To do
       so, follow the steps bellow:
      </para>
    </abstract>
  </info>
  <procedure>
    <step>
      <para>
        Verify the slot status by running the command:
      </para>
      <screen>&prompt.sudo;<command>ls /sys/devices/system/memory/</command></screen>      
    </step>
    <step>
      <para>
        Insert the RAM module. The motherboard firmware recognizes the new silicon, safely routes power to the slot, and broadcasts a physical ACPI interrupt signal (PNP0C80) directly to the host Linux kernel.
      </para>
    </step>
    <step>
      <para>
        Verify that the machine successfully accepted the hardware by running: 
      </para>
      <screen>&prompt.sudo;<command>grep .
      /sys/devices/system/memory/memory*/state</command></screen>
      <para>
        The new <literal>memoryXXX</literal> directories appear at the bottom of the list, all automatically marked as <literal>online</literal>.
      </para>
    </step>
  </procedure>
</topic>
